<Layout title="Morning Briefing - 07/22/26: Power Grab TX">
  <div class="post-page">
    <div class="post-content">
      <h1>⭐ Morning Briefing — Texas &amp; DFW AI Data Centers, Grid, Land Use</h1>
      <p class="briefing-subtitle">(Latest updates through July 22, 2026)</p>

      <hr class="section-divider" />

      <h2>⚡ 1. ERCOT &amp; Grid Signals</h2>
      <p class="section-tagline">EPA's Minor-Source Permitting Hearing Happens Today — Batch Zero Deadline Two Days Out</p>
      <ul>
        <li>The EPA holds its virtual public hearing today, July 22, 9 a.m.–3 p.m. CT, on the proposed rollback of public-notice requirements for "minor source" air permits — the category covering most data-center backup generators and gas turbines. This is the last live public forum before any rule change takes effect; written comments stay open through August 21 (see Item 3).</li>
        <li>The Batch Zero technical-package deadline is now two days away: TSPs/DSPs serving large-load projects (including DFW-area ones) must submit full technical packages to ERCOT by Friday, July 24, with classification notices due back to interconnecting large loads by August 7.</li>
        <li>Gov. Abbott's July 17 deadline for the PUC and ERCOT to jointly submit a ratepayer-safeguard memo has now passed by five days with no public release or confirmation of filing surfacing in coverage today.</li>
        <li>The nearer-term Abbott deadline remains the PUC's July 31 obligation to act on reducing residential ratepayers' transmission costs — nine days out. ERCOT's systemwide large-load queue remains north of 438,000 MW, roughly 89% of it tied to data centers.</li>
      </ul>
      <p class="signal"><strong>Today's Signal:</strong> Today's EPA hearing is the day's clearest live event — worth watching for turnout and any TCEQ reaction, since the outcome directly shapes future notice requirements for DFW-area gas and diesel permits.</p>

      <hr class="section-divider" />

      <h2>🏗️ 2. Data Center Construction &amp; Corporate Activity</h2>
      <p class="section-tagline">No New Dated Announcement Today — Recent Deals Still the Active Storylines</p>
      <ul>
        <li>No new construction or corporate filing dated specifically to today surfaced from the core DFW hyperscaler/PE names (Meta, AWS, Google, Microsoft) or from recent regional movers.</li>
        <li>Hedgehog USA's July 21 agreement with Idemitsu to fuel a 600 MW "powered land" campus in Navarro County — just south of the DFW metro along the I-45 corridor — remains the most recent concrete construction signal near the metro.</li>
        <li>The Plug Power sale of its Graham, Texas site (Young County, northwest of DFW) — land plus 164 MW of grid interconnection assets — to Stream Data Centers remains on track to close on or about July 31, for up to $76.5 million plus roughly $14 million in released cash collateral.</li>
        <li>BlackRock/ACS's Coravel platform 140 MW DFW campus commitment (announced July 15) and Black Mountain's 2,000-plus-acre Fort Worth-area purchase remain the other live threads inside the metro core.</li>
      </ul>
      <p class="signal"><strong>Today's Signal:</strong> With nothing new dated today, the Plug Power/Stream Graham transaction's expected July 31 close is the next concrete DFW-adjacent milestone to watch.</p>

      <hr class="section-divider" />

      <h2>🌿 3. Environmental &amp; Air-Permit Activity (TCEQ)</h2>
      <p class="section-tagline">EPA Public Hearing Live Today — No New DFW-County TCEQ Filing</p>
      <ul>
        <li>No new dated TCEQ draft permit or public-comment notice specific to Collin, Ellis, Johnson, Denton, Wise, Tarrant, Parker, or Hood counties surfaced today.</li>
        <li>The dominant storyline is today's EPA virtual public hearing (9 a.m.–3 p.m. CT) on rolling back public-participation requirements for minor-source air permits — the category covering many of the diesel generators and gas turbines powering Texas data centers. Written comments remain open through August 21.</li>
        <li>Recurring statewide figures still being cited in coverage: at least 38 Texas data centers have received minor-source permits for on-site power since 2024, enabling more than 2,100 backup diesel generators statewide; proposed facilities statewide could emit more than 287 million tons of greenhouse gases annually.</li>
        <li>Pacifico Energy's GW Ranch project in Pecos County remains the largest air permit ever granted in the U.S. — 7.65 GW of gas-fired generation for hyperscale data centers — cited by advocates as evidence TCEQ's minor-source review process is being outpaced by the industry it regulates.</li>
      </ul>
      <p class="signal"><strong>Today's Signal:</strong> Today's EPA hearing is the live event to track — its outcome will determine how much advance notice DFW-area communities get on future gas- and diesel-generator permits.</p>

      <hr class="section-divider" />

      <h2>🏛️ 4. Land-Use &amp; Zoning Developments</h2>
      <p class="section-tagline">Fort Worth and Denton Still Pointing to Later Dates — Nothing New Filed Today</p>
      <ul>
        <li>No new DFW-area county rezoning filing or vote surfaced dated specifically to today.</li>
        <li>Fort Worth's zoning fight remains set for August 11, when City Council reconvenes from summer break to take up the data-center ordinance the Zoning Commission denied 7-4 on July 8. A Fort Worth Report piece published yesterday (July 21) examined whether the proposed moratorium can produce a meaningful long-term solution or just delay the underlying zoning fight. Five council members (Beck, Flores, Hall, Martinez, Nettles) remain on record backing a temporary moratorium; Mayor Parker and three others have not signed on.</li>
        <li>Denton's push remains in an earlier stage than Fort Worth's: City Council directed staff in early June to explore a possible moratorium, and a July 16 community town hall kept pressure on the issue, but no formal council vote date has been set.</li>
        <li>Earlier flashpoints remain unresolved in the background: Parker County's pushback over Black Mountain's 2,000-plus-acre purchase, and Hood County's conditional approval of the 2,100-acre "Comanche Circle" proposal near Glen Rose.</li>
      </ul>
      <p class="signal"><strong>Today's Signal:</strong> With Fort Worth's council vote three weeks out and Denton still without a set date, today is a quiet day on DFW land use — yesterday's Fort Worth Report analysis is worth a read for context heading into August.</p>

      <hr class="section-divider" />

      <h2>🔌 5. Power-First Strategies &amp; On-Site Generation</h2>
      <p class="section-tagline">No New Dated Deal Today — Navarro County and Pecos Projects Remain the Marquee Stories</p>
      <ul>
        <li>No new on-site generation or gas-plant announcement dated specifically to today surfaced.</li>
        <li>Hedgehog USA's July 21 agreement with Idemitsu (Item 2) remains the most recent power-first signal: a 600 MW campus built to run on natural gas burned on-site, explicitly avoiding the multi-year ERCOT interconnection queue.</li>
        <li>Equipment bottlenecks continue to be cited as the structural driver: switchgear reportedly sold out through 2028, and substation transformer lead times stretched to roughly 160 weeks and rising.</li>
        <li>The Chevron-Microsoft 20-year power purchase agreement for a dedicated natural-gas plant near Pecos (roughly 2.5 GW initially, ~$7 billion, targeting 2027) and Microsoft's separate ~2.67 GW co-located gas plant for Project Kilby remain the marquee statewide power-first deals. The pending EPA minor-source rollback (Item 3, hearing today) would directly ease the permitting path for the diesel and gas behind-the-meter fleets DFW-region data centers rely on to satisfy Senate Bill 6's backup-generation requirement for facilities of 75 MW or more.</li>
      </ul>
      <p class="signal"><strong>Today's Signal:</strong> Today's EPA hearing (Item 3) is the cross-cutting story for this section too — its outcome affects how easily operators can permit the on-site generation power-first strategies depend on.</p>

      <hr class="section-divider" />

      <h2>📍 6. Today's Watch List</h2>
      <p class="section-tagline">Actionable Signals for Wednesday</p>

      <h3>ERCOT</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Turnout and testimony at today's (July 22) EPA hearing on minor-source permitting rollback</li>
        <li>TSP/DSP technical package submissions ahead of the July 24 Batch Zero deadline</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>PUC</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Any public confirmation that the PUC/ERCOT ratepayer-safeguard memo (due July 17) was actually filed</li>
        <li>Follow-through on Abbott's July 31 deadline for the PUC to act on residential transmission-cost reductions</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>TCEQ</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Written comments accumulating ahead of the August 21 deadline on the EPA minor-source rule</li>
        <li>Any new draft air permits or public-comment notices for gas-fired generation near DFW counties</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>County Zoning (DFW + Surrounding Counties)</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Fort Worth City Council's August 11 vote on the data-center zoning ordinance/moratorium</li>
        <li>Denton City Council's next step — no formal moratorium vote date set yet</li>
        <li>Any new county-level moratorium proposals following recent organizing activity</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Corporate Filings</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Close of the Plug Power/Stream Data Centers Graham, Texas transaction, expected on or about July 31</li>
        <li>Progress on Hedgehog USA/Idemitsu's Navarro County "powered land" campus</li>
        <li>Any new interconnection or air-permit filings from Meta, AWS, Google, or Microsoft in the DFW region</li>
      </ul>

